Shared Qs (003)

  1. Question

    Determine the probability that the standard normal variable is less than 0.22. In other words, evaluate \(P(Z < 0.22)\).


    Solution

    (ANS=0.5871)

    video

    The numbers that satisfy \(Z<0.22\) are on the left side of a number line (toward \(-\infty\)). The probability equals a left area under the density curve.


    By using the z-table, we find the appropriate probability. \[P(Z<0.22)=0.5871\]

    It might help to visualize with a spinner:


    Using a spreadsheet:

    =NORM.DIST(0.22,0,1,TRUE)

    Using R:

    pnorm(0.22)

  2. Question

    Determine the probability that the standard normal variable is more than 0.59. In other words, evaluate \(P(Z > 0.59)\).


    Solution

    (ANS=0.2776)

    video

    First, you need to identify that we are looking for a right area. This is because large values of \(Z\) satisfy \(Z>0.59\).


    By using the z-table, we find the left area (even though we eventually want the right area).

    \[P(Z<0.59)=0.7224\]

    We use the rule of compliments to determine the right area.

    \[\begin{aligned} P(Z > 0.59) &= 1-P(Z < 0.59) \\ &= 1-0.7224 \\ &= 0.2776 \end{aligned}\]

    Method 2: You might also recognize that the normal distribution is symmetric. Thus,

    \[\begin{aligned} P(Z > 0.59) &= P(Z < -0.59) \\ &= 0.2776 \end{aligned}\]

    Method 3: It often helps to draw a picture.


    It might help to visualize with a spinner:


    Using a spreadsheet:

    =1-NORM.DIST(0.59,0,1,TRUE)

    Using R:

    1-pnorm(0.59)

  3. Question

    Determine the probability that the absolute standard normal variable is less than 0.75. In other words, evaluate \(P\left(|Z| < 0.75\right)\).


    Solution

    (ANS=0.5468)

    video

    First, you need to identify that we are looking for a central area. This is because \(z\)-scores near 0 satisfy \(|Z|<0.75\), while \(z\)-scores far from 0 (either positive or negative) do not satisfy the inequality.

    Start with a sketch.


    Remember, the entire area is always 1. Most z-tables only provide left areas, so three methods are shown to get the central area from a left-area (cumulative probability) table.

    Method 1: First find the area of the left tail. \[P(Z<-0.75) = 0.2266\] Recognize normal distributions are symmetric, so we also know the area of the right tail. \[P(Z>0.75) = 0.2266 \] The three areas add to 1. \[\begin{aligned} P\left(|Z|<0.75\right) &= 1-P(Z<-0.75)-P(Z>0.75) \\ &= 1 - 0.2266 - 0.2266 \\ &= 0.5468 \end{aligned}\]

    This technique can be summarized with the following formula: \[P\left(|Z|<z\right) = 1-2\cdot P(Z<-z)\] assuming \(z>0\).

    So, in our case (when \(z=0.75\)), \[\begin{aligned} P\left(|Z|<0.75\right) &= 1-2\cdot P(Z<-0.75) \\ &= 1-2\cdot0.2266 \\ &= 0.5468 \end{aligned}\]

    This method is shown graphically:


    Method 2: You can also find half of the central area and then double it. \[\begin{aligned} P\left(|Z|<z\right) &= 2\cdot\left[ P(Z<z)-0.5\right] \\ &= 2\cdot\left[ 0.7734-0.5\right] \\ &= 2\cdot\left[ 0.2734\right] \\ &= 0.5468 \end{aligned}\]

    This method is shown graphically:


    Method 3: You can also calculate the central area with a difference of two left areas.

    \[\begin{aligned} P\left(|Z|<0.75\right) &= P(Z<0.75)-P(Z<-0.75)\\ &= 0.7734-0.2266 \\ &= 0.5468 \end{aligned}\]


    It might be helpful to visualize with a spinner.


    In a spreadsheet, you could use the NORM.DIST() function.

    =NORM.DIST(0.75,0,1,TRUE) - NORM.DIST(-0.75,0,1,TRUE)

    In R, you could use the pnorm function.

    pnorm(0.75) - pnorm(-0.75)

  4. Question

    Determine the probability that the absolute standard normal variable is more than 0.9. In other words, evaluate \(P\left(|Z| > 0.9\right)\).


    Solution

    (ANS=0.3682)

    video

    First, you need to identify that we are looking for a two-tail area (the sum of the left and right tails). This is because \(z\)-scores far from 0 satisfy \(|Z|>0.9\), while \(z\)-scores near 0 do not satisfy the inequality.

    Start with a sketch.


    Remember, the entire area is always 1. Most z-tables only provides left areas, so three methods are shown to get the two-tail area from a left-area (cumulative probability) table.

    Method 1: First find the area of the left tail. \[P(Z<-0.9) = 0.1841\] Recognize normal distributions are symmetric, so we also know the area of the right tail. \[P(Z>0.9) = 0.1841 \] The two areas add to our desired two-tail area. \[\begin{aligned} P\left(|Z|>0.9\right) &= P(Z<-0.9)+P(Z>0.9) \\ &= 0.1841 + 0.1841 \\ &= 0.3682 \end{aligned}\]

    This technique can be summarized with the following formula: \[P\left(|Z|>z\right) = 2\cdot P(Z<-z)\] assuming \(z>0\).

    So, in our case (when \(z=0.9\)), \[\begin{aligned} P\left(|Z|<0.9\right) &= 2\cdot P(Z<-0.9) \\ &= 2\cdot0.1841 \\ &= 0.3682 \end{aligned}\]

    This method is shown graphically:


    Notice we need to add both tails.

    Method 2: You can achieve the same result by using the following formula: \[P\left(|Z|>z\right) = 2\cdot\left[1-P(Z<z) \right] \] So, \[\begin{aligned} P\left(|Z|>0.9\right) &= 2\cdot\left[1-P(Z<0.9) \right] \\ &= 2\cdot\left[1-0.8159\right] \\ &= 2\cdot0.1841\\ &= 0.3682 \end{aligned}\]

    It might be helpful to visualize with a spinner.


    In a spreadsheet, you could use the NORM.DIST() function.

    =2*NORM.DIST(-0.9,0,1,TRUE)

    In R, you could use the pnorm function.

    2*pnorm(-0.9)

  5. Question

    Determine the probability that the standard normal variable is between -1.88 and 0.08. In other words, evaluate \(P(-1.88 < Z < 0.08)\).


    Solution

    (ANS=0.5018)

    video

    Start with a sketch.


    We take a difference of areas. \[\begin{aligned} P(-1.88<Z<0.08) &= P(Z<0.08) - P(Z<-1.88) \\ &= 0.5319 - 0.0301 \\ &= 0.5018 \end{aligned}\]



    In a spreadsheet, you could use the NORM.DIST() function.

    =NORM.DIST(0.08,0,1,TRUE) - NORM.DIST(-1.88,0,1,TRUE)

    In R, you could use the pnorm function.

    pnorm(0.08) - pnorm(-1.88)

  6. Question

    Determine \(z\) such that \(P(Z<z)=0.43\). In other words, what \(z\)-score is greater than \(43\)% of standard normal values? (Answers within 0.01 from the correct value will be marked correct.)


    Solution

    (ANS=-0.1763742)

    video

    Start with a sketch. Leftward numbers (toward \(-\infty\)) will be less than our boundary \(z\), so we shade a left region with area 0.43.


    You should go to your \(z\)-table and find the \(z\)-score with the left area closest to 0.43.

    \(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
    -0.2 0.4207
    -0.19 0.4247
    -0.18 0.4286
    -0.17 0.4325
    -0.16 0.4364
    -0.15 0.4404

    It turns out the exact answer is \(z=-0.1763742\), which could be found by using an inverse normal function. On a spreadsheet:

    =Norm.Inv(0.43,0,1)

    Using R:

    qnorm(0.43)

    But, the \(z\)-table is accurate enough, so I will accept either -0.18 or -0.17 (anything within 0.01 of -0.1763742).

    You might find it helpful to visualize with a spinner.



  7. Question

    Determine \(z\) such that \(P(Z>z)=0.9\). In other words, what \(z\)-score is less than \(90\)% of standard normal values? (Answers within 0.01 from the correct value will be marked correct.)


    Solution

    (ANS=-1.2815516)

    video

    Start with a sketch. Rightward numbers (toward \(+\infty\)) will be more than our boundary \(z\), so we shade a rightward region with area 0.9.


    You should first find the left area. \[\begin{aligned} P(Z<z) &= 1-P(Z>z) \\ &= 1-0.9 \\ &= 0.1 \end{aligned}\]


    You should go to your \(z\)-table and find the \(z\)-score with the left area closest to 0.1.

    \(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
    -1.31 0.0951
    -1.3 0.0968
    -1.29 0.0985
    -1.28 0.1003
    -1.27 0.102
    -1.26 0.1038

    It turns out the exact answer is \(z=-1.2815516\), which could be found by using an inverse normal function. On a spreadsheet:

    =Norm.Inv(0.1,0,1)

    Using R:

    rightarea = 0.9
leftarea = 1-rightarea
qnorm( leftarea )

    But, the \(z\)-table is accurate enough, so I will accept either -1.29 or -1.28 (anything within 0.01 of -1.2815516).

    You might find it helpful to visualize with a spinner.



  8. Question

    Determine \(z\) such that \(P(|Z|<z)=0.62\). In other words, how far from 0 should boundaries be set such that 62% of standard normal values are between those boundaries? (Answers within 0.01 from the correct value will be marked correct.)


    Solution

    (ANS=0.8778963)

    video

    Start with a sketch.


    Method 1: Determine the area of each tail. Both tails have the same area, and all three areas add to 1. Thus, \[P(Z>z) = \frac{1-0.62}{2} = 0.19\]

    \[\begin{aligned} P(Z<z) &= 0.19+0.62 \\ &= 0.81 \end{aligned}\]

    You should go to your \(z\)-table and find the \(z\)-score with the left area closest to 0.81.

    \(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
    0.85 0.8023
    0.86 0.8051
    0.87 0.8078
    0.88 0.8106
    0.89 0.8133
    0.9 0.8159

    It turns out the exact answer is \(z=0.8778963\), which could be found by using an inverse normal function. On a spreadsheet:

    =Norm.Inv(0.81,0,1)

    Using R:

    centralarea = 0.62
leftarea = (1-centralarea)/2 + centralarea
qnorm( leftarea )

    But, because we are using the \(z\)-table, I will accept either 0.87 or 0.88. (Or, really anything within 0.01 of 0.8778963.)

    Method 2: Another way to get 0.81 is by adding half of 0.62 to 0.5. \[P(Z<z) ~=~ \frac{0.62}{2}+0.5~=~ 0.31+0.5 ~=~ 0.81\]


    Then, use the table. Or, you could use R:

    centralarea = 0.62
leftarea = 0.5 + centralarea/2
qnorm( leftarea )

    It might be helpful to visualize with a spinner.



  9. Question

    Determine \(z\) such that \(P(|Z|>z)=0.36\). In other words, how far from 0 should boundaries be set such that 36% of standard normal values are outside those boundaries? (Answers within 0.01 from the correct value will be marked correct.)


    Solution

    (ANS=0.9153651)

    video

    Start with a sketch. The total two-tail area is 0.36, so each tail has half that area.


    Method 1: Determine the area of each tail and the center. Both tails have the same area, and all three areas add to 1. Thus, \[P(Z>z) = \frac{0.36}{2} = 0.18\]

    \[P(Z<-z) = \frac{0.36}{2} = 0.18\]

    \[\begin{aligned} P(|Z|<z) &= 1-P(|Z|>z) \\ &= 1-0.36 \\ &= 0.64 \end{aligned}\]

    Find the left area.

    \[\begin{aligned} P(Z<z) &= 0.18+0.64 \\ &= 0.82 \end{aligned}\]

    You should go to your \(z\)-table and find the \(z\)-score with the left area closest to 0.82.

    \(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
    0.89 0.8133
    0.9 0.8159
    0.91 0.8186
    0.92 0.8212
    0.93 0.8238
    0.94 0.8264

    It turns out the exact answer is \(z=0.9153651\), which could be found by using an inverse normal function. On a spreadsheet:

    =Norm.Inv(0.82,0,1)

    Using R:

    twotailarea = 0.36
onetailarea = twotailarea/2
centralarea = 1-twotailarea
leftarea = onetailarea + centralarea
qnorm( leftarea )

    Method 2: Another way to get 0.82 is by subtracting half of 0.36 from 1. \[P(Z<z) ~=~ 1-\frac{0.36}{2}~=~ 1-0.18 ~=~ 0.82\]


    Then, use the table. Or, R:

    twotailarea = 0.36
leftarea = 1 - twotailarea/2
qnorm( leftarea )

    You might find a spinner visualization useful.
